UND Housing & Residence Life Knowledge Base

Source: www.housing.und.edu
Context: This document contains the "Truthful" operational data for the Guiding NORTH training app. Use this to validate facts, fees, and policy explanations.

1. Contact & Operations

Housing Office

Physical Location: 3 Strinden Rd, Grand Forks, ND 58202 (Located at University Place).

Mailing Address: 525 Stanford Rd, Stop 9029.

Phone: 701.777.4251

Email: housing@UND.edu

Standard Office Hours:

Monday - Friday: 8:00 AM – 4:30 PM

Saturday & Sunday: Closed

Wilkerson Service Center:

Hub for mail/packages and key checkouts for residence halls.

After-Hours Protocol

Emergency Maintenance: Contact the RA on Duty or the specific Loan Key Desk for the building.

Lockouts (After Hours): Contact the RA on Duty or Wilkerson Service Center (if open).

Voicemails: Messages left after close (4:30 PM) are reviewed the next business morning.

2. Facilities (Halls & Apartments)

Residence Halls

Suite Style (Shared bath between 2 rooms): McVey Hall, West Hall, Brannon Hall, Noren Hall, Selke Hall.

Community Style (Shared floor bath): Smith Hall, Johnstone Hall (often referenced as Smith/Johnstone complex).

Apartment Style (In-unit kitchen/bath): University Place, Swanson Hall.

Amenities: Free laundry, high-speed internet (ResNet), 24-hour secured access, kitchenette/microwave stations.

Apartments

Locations: Berkeley Drive, Carleton Court, Hamline Square, Mt. Vernon/Williamsburg, Swanson Complex, Tulane Court, Virginia Rose, 3904 University Ave.

Included: Internet (Midco), Water/Sewer/Trash.

Electricity: Paid by resident (setup via Xcel Energy).

Pet Policy: Generally no pets (except fish/Service Animals/ESAs) unless specified in specific pet-friendly units (check current lease terms).

3. Key Policies (The Handbook)

Guest Policy

Limit: Guests may stay no more than 3 consecutive nights.

Frequency: Maximum of 6 nights total per month.

Escort Rule: Guests must be escorted by the host resident at all times (24/7) within the building.

Consent: Roommate(s) must approve of the guest presence.

Minors: Guests under 18 are generally prohibited unless immediate family (policy varies by hall/apartment context).

Alcohol & Drugs

Under 21: STRICTLY PROHIBITED. Possession or consumption is a violation.

21+ Areas: Alcohol permitted only in rooms where all assigned residents are 21+.

Paraphernalia: Beer bongs, kegs, and funnels are prohibited regardless of age.

Empty Containers: Prohibited in rooms where residents are under 21.

Quiet Hours

Standard Hours:

Sunday - Thursday: 10:00 PM – 10:00 AM

Friday - Saturday: 12:00 AM (Midnight) – 10:00 AM

Courtesy Hours: 24 hours a day. Noise should not be audible outside the room.

Finals Week: 24-hour quiet hours are enforced.

Lockouts & Keys

Procedure: Visit Wilkerson Service Center or call RA on Duty.

Business Hours Fee: $10.00

After Hours Fee: $25.00

Lost Key (Recore): $75.00 charge to change the core (mandatory for security).

4. Operational Processes

Room Changes

The "Freeze": No room changes are permitted during the first 2 weeks of any semester (Census period).

Process:

Resident meets with Resident Director (RD) first.

RD submits request to Housing Office.

Offer made based on availability (Wednesdays).

Unauthorized Moves: Moving without approval results in a fine ($100+) and required return to original space.

Maintenance Requests

Routine: Submit via the Maintenance Request Portal (online). Response typically within 2 business days.

Emergency (Flood, No Heat, Lock Broken):

During Business Hours: Call 701.777.4251.

After Hours: Call RA on Duty immediately. Do not submit online.

Move-Out (Apartments)

Notice: "Notice to Vacate" form required via Housing Self Service (typically 60 days notice for lease break or standard end of term).

Modem: Residents must NOT take the Midco modem/equipment.

Fine: $165.00 charge if modem is removed.

Cleaning: Residents must clean oven, fridge, bathroom, and floors to avoid cleaning fees.

5. Staff Role Specifics (For AI Persona)

Front Desk: Can handle lockouts, general questions, mail. Cannot approve room changes or waive fees.

Resident Director (RD): Handles roommate conflicts, room change requests, conduct meetings.

Housing Operations: Handles billing, assignments, lease terminations.

6. Policies, Contracts & Rates (2025-2026)

First-Year Live-On Requirement

Policy: All first-year students are required to live in a residence hall on-campus for their first, full academic year.

First-Year Definition: Undergraduate students who enroll full-time within one year of high school graduation (or equivalent) AND have less than 24 transferable post-secondary credit hours.

Exemptions: May be requested if:

Residing with parent/guardian within 35 miles of campus.

21+ years of age.

Married or have dependents.

Enrolled less than full-time.

Housing Contracts

Residence Halls:

Term: Contracts are for the Full Academic Year (Fall & Spring Semesters).

Cancellation: Once moved in, students are financially responsible for the entire contract unless they withdraw from the University.

Break Housing: Winter Break housing is included at no additional cost for students returning for Spring.

Apartments:

Lease Types:

Academic Year Agreement: August – May.

12-Month Agreement: May – May (or August – August for some units).

Cancellation: Requires a 60-Day Notice to Vacate submitted via Housing Self Service.

Rates (2025-2026 Snapshot)

Residence Halls (Per Academic Year):

Double Room (Standard): ~$5,100 – $6,180 (varies by hall).

Single Room: ~$5,900 – $7,300 (varies by hall and amenities).

Meal Plans: First-year students are required to have an Anytime Access meal plan (Platinum or Gold).

Apartments (Monthly Rates):

One Bedroom: ~$735 – $845/month (varies by location/furnishings).

Two Bedroom: ~$830 – $935/month.

Three Bedroom: ~$1,010 – $1,400/month.

Included Utilities: Internet, Water, Sewer, Trash. (Electricity is paid separately by resident).